What Happens When You Use @JoinColumn Without @ManyToMany?

1. @JoinColumn with @ManyToOne or @OneToOne
When you use @JoinColumn with @ManyToOne or @OneToOne, no third (join) table is created.
Instead, a foreign key column is added directly to the table of the entity where the
annotation is used.

Example: @ManyToOne

@Entity
public class Post {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @ManyToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "user_id") // Foreign key in Post table
    private User user;
}

Result:

The Post table will have a user_id column that is a foreign key referencing the User table.
No extra table is created.

Example: @OneToOne

@Entity
public class User {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @OneToOne
    @JoinColumn(name = "profile_id") // Foreign key in User table
    private Profile profile;
}

Result:
The User table will have a profile_id column referencing the Profile table.
No extra table is created.

2. @JoinColumn with @ManyToMany
Only in a @ManyToMany relationship does JPA create a third (join) table to manage the
relationship.
This is because neither side can hold a foreign key to the other without duplicating data
or breaking normalization.

Summary Table

Relationship Type	     @JoinColumn Effect	                            Extra Table Created?

@ManyToOne	             Adds FK column to owning entity’s table	         No
@OneToOne	             Adds FK column to owning entity’s table	         No
@ManyToMany	             Creates a join table with FKs to both entities	     Yes

In short:

@JoinColumn with @ManyToOne or @OneToOne → Adds a foreign key column, no third table.
@JoinColumn with @ManyToMany (inside @JoinTable) → Creates a third (join) table.

Info:
In Many To Many a third table is created for better visualisation and it bit better
normalisation.

